ngs—Automatic Architecture offers an alternative to narratives of this period that have presented postmodernism as a question of style, as the methods and techniques traced here have been more deeply consequential than the many stylistic shifts of the past half century. Sean Keller closes the book with an analysis of the contemporary condition, suggesting future paths for architectural practice that work through, but also beyond, the merely automatic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArchitectural designxHistoryy20th century. 0aArchitectural designxPhilosophy. 0aArchitectural design-History-20th century. 0aArchitectural design-Philosophy. 0aArchitecture, Moderny20th century. 0aArchitecture, Modern-20th century. 0aArchitecture, Postmodern. 0aEisenman, Peter,-1932-. 0aOtto, Frei,-1925-2015. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh  aarchitecture.  aautomatic.  apostwar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978022649649840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226496528423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226496528/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles